Diagnosis.

Leucania rawlinsi

can be distinguished from several American congeners by the dark brown dorsal forewing ground color, darker over the cubitus; the presence of a small white dot at the end of the discal cell; a somewhat triangular caramel patch between the end of the discal cell and the apex, crossed by dark brown lines at the middle of the space of veins; and the postdiscal area with a row of dark dots over the veins (
Figs 1–2
). However, the above cited characters are also present in some other members of the genus. Thus, the species can be identified confidently only by the examination of the male genitalia, in which the valva is about as long as wide; the sacculus is rounded and narrowed dorsally; the cucullus is knob-like and distally expanded; the digitus and clasper are short and pointed, both arranged in a C-shaped aspect; the aedeagus has a simple vesica, without an appendix, and bears two long, distally curved cornuti (
Fig. 9
). In the female genitalia the ductus bursae is laterally narrow, gradually membranous towards the appendix bursae and as long as the corpus bursae; the appendix bursae is longer than the ductus bursae, bent left and coiled, with the proximal area broad; and the corpus bursae is ovoid, completely membranous, and lack a signum (
Fig. 11
).

Abdomen
: Brown, dorsally darker in males, with two grayish black spots over tergum I and II (
Fig. 6
). Tip of abdomen densely covered by light cream scales (
Figs 1–2
).
